Five truths about terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is hostage to terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one out of six Americans, about 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
For ten years, never have so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, although their number is still much lower than the 46% recorded in the aftermath of the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were most evident during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), certainly benefited from this.
Some politicians are allowed to refer to the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But presidential candidates, just like some media outlets, who adhere to the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists care more about capturing attention and dominating political headlines than about the number, in itself, of their victims.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The brutal beheadings broadcast on social networks are intended to destabilize and scandalize – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills far less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than to be killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be murdered by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of 1 in 950,000), from a household appliance accident (a probability of 1 in 1.5 million), from a deer or moose crossing the road (a probability of 1 in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (a probability of 1 in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving by texting or talking on their cell phones.
This is hundreds of times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings on college campuses or in schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist surge.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Armed Revolutionary Faction, emerging from the "autonomous" left, diverted planes out of national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon dressed in religious clothing.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imagined and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIS will ultimately be defeated, just as previous transnational terrorist movements have been.
Terrorism is like judo.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat him.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to draw Americans into Afghanistan.
ISIS emerged from the ruins of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, one needs smart power.
Smart power is the ability to combine the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Soft power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and prevent the irredeemables from recruiting them.
This is why attention to the narrative of events and how U.S. actions are commented on social networks is as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts all of us in danger.
The reason why the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential election candidates is so counterproductive.
Terrorism is a serious issue, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It is an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of terrorists' reach.
But we must not fall into the trap set by terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and hoodlums take place.
If we leave them the grand stage of our public discourse, we will weaken the quality of our civic life and betray our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
